HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1331
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor sideline cheerleading and its
contributions to the culture, spirit, and athletic
success of schools and communities across the
State of Tennessee.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly are pleased to specially honor and
commend those students who, through their dedication and spirit, serve as the heart of school
athletics and essential ambassadors for this State; and
WHEREAS, sideline cheerleading is a storied tradition in Tennessee that serves as a
cornerstone of school spirit, fostering an environment of enthusiasm and support that motivates
student athletes to perform at their highest level; and
WHEREAS, beyond their role as "the team behind the team," sideline cheerleaders are
highly skilled athletes who develop exceptional coordination, physical endurance, and mental
focus through rigorous training and practice; and
WHEREAS, participation in sideline cheerleading instills invaluable life skills, including
leadership, teamwork, discipline, and time management, preparing young Tennesseans for
success in higher education and their future careers; and
WHEREAS, these athletes act as community leaders, bridging the gap between the
student body, alumni, and the public to create a unified sense of pride and camaraderie during
athletic events and community outreach initiatives; and
WHEREAS, it is appropriate that this General Assembly honor the tireless efforts of
these dedicated individuals who often sacrifice their time and energy to ensure that the spirit of
Tennessee's schools remains vibrant and strong; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
HJR1331
017492
- 1 -

CONCURRING, that we hereby honor sideline cheerleading and commend the thousands of
student athletes across this State who serve their schools and communities with such
distinction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
